 "components": {
  "instruction": "Classify the provided user input text into exactly one category from the following list, based on the intended action, query, or topic implied by the user's words:\n\nalarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nUse the following domain-specific information to improve your classifications:\n\n- Task: You are not just identifying the topic, you must also detect the user's intent (e.g., \"set\", \"query\", \"remove\", \"order\", \"play\").\n- Distinguish between similar categories by the user's action: \n    - If the user wants to set or add something to a calendar, such as \"repeat birthday\", classify as 'calendar_set'. \n    - If the user is querying or asking about calendar items/events, use 'calendar_query'.\n    - For intent to delete or remove from a list (including music libraries), such as \"delete the song what if in my music\", classify as 'lists_remove', not 'play_music'.\n    - When querying for the definition, fact, or stock/currency info, choose 'qa_definition', 'qa_factoid', 'qa_stock', or 'qa_currency' as applicable.\n    - For queries about general user-generated content or platform interactions (like \"customer service feedback\"), use 'social_post'.\n- \"Music\", \"audiobook\", \"podcast\", and \"radio\" interact with content: \"play_\" is for requests to play, \"music_query\" is for asking for music information.\n- \"lists_createoradd\" is for adding items to a list, \"lists_query\" is for checking what’s on a list, \"lists_remove\" for removal.\n- \"calendar_remove\" is only for deleting events.\n- \"email_sendemail\" is for sending, \"email_query\" for checking or finding email content.\n- \"alarm_set\" and \"alarm_query\" are distinct: setting versus querying alarms.\n- \"iot_hue_lightoff\" is specifically for turning off Hue lights.\n\nOutput only one category label from the list. Do not provide explanations or definitions. Base your answer primarily on the action implied by the user's words, not just the keywords present."
 },
